 the history of Alzheimer's disease and extensive in-depth interviews, Margaret Lock highlights the limitations and the dissent associated with biomarker detection. Lock argues that basic research must continue, but should be complemented by a public health approach to prevention that is economically feasible, more humane, and much more effective globally than one exclusively focused on an increasingly harried search for a cure.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAlzheimer's diseasexAge factors. 0aAlzheimer's disease. 0aBrainxAgingxMolecular aspects. 0aDementia. 0aElectronic books. 0aOlder peoplexMental health. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aAPOE.  aAlois Alzheimer.  aAlzheimer disease.  aAlzheimer enterprise.  aAlzheimer genetics.  aAlzheimer prevention.  aAlzheimer world.  aAlzheimer's disease.  aDNA samples.  aDNA.  aGWAS.  aHuntington disease.  aaging population.  aaging populations.  aaging societies.  aamyloid cascade hypothesis.  aamyloid cascade process.  abehavioral changes.  abiomarkers.  abiosociality.  abreast cancer.  aclinical diagnosis.  aclinical settings.  acontrol samples.  adementia.  adiagnosis.  adivination.  aearly-onset.  aenvironmental variables.  aepidemiological research.  aepidemiology.  aepigenetics.  aethnographic research.  aexpert knowledge.  afamily practice settings.  agene function.  agenes.  agenetic testing.  ageneticization.  agenome-wide association studies.  agenomics.  aglobal economy.  alate-onset.  alocalization theory.  amedical publications.  amemory clinics.  amemory loss.  amicro-medical management.  amild cognitive impairment.  amolecular approach.  amolecular biologists.  amolecularization.  aneuritic amyloid plaques.  aneurofibril